“The sharing economy is becoming a part of our everyday lives,” Chang told CalWatchdog.com.
“By allowing state employees to use the sharing economy, California is leading by example and embracing innovation,” Chang explained.
With more than 271,000 active state employees, a shift by state government to more sharing services could help save taxpayers money.
Chang’s office says that state employees have been reimbursed approximately $110 million in travel-related expenses over the last three years.
The bill has run headlong into opposition from one state lawmaker that has consistently opposed the new sharing economy.